@title{LateralusOS Phase 3: The Interactive Desktop}
@author{bad-antics}
@date{2026-03-31}
@tags{lateralus, os, gui, terminal, filesystem, speaker, animation}

@section{Overview}

Phase 3 of LateralusOS transforms the graphical desktop from a static window manager
into a fully interactive environment. The kernel has grown from 136 KB to 375 KB,
gaining four major new subsystems and numerous GUI enhancements — all while maintaining
a clean zero-warning build.

@section{What's New}

@subsection{Functional GUI Terminal}

The centerpiece of Phase 3 is a real, working terminal emulator rendered inside
the framebuffer GUI. Each terminal gets its own window, its own scrollback buffer
(200 lines, 80 columns), and its own working directory.

@code[ltl]{
// 17 built-in commands:
// File ops:    ls, cat, touch, mkdir, rm, cd, pwd
// Output:      echo (supports echo text > file redirect)
// System:      uname, uptime, free, tasks
// Terminal:    help, clear, history, neofetch
}

Up to 4 terminals can run simultaneously. Each has cursor blinking (500 ms),
command history with Up/Down arrows (16 entries), and full VFS path resolution
(absolute paths with @code{..} support).

@subsection{RAM Filesystem (ramfs)}

A proper inode-based in-memory filesystem. 64 max nodes, 16 children per directory,
2 KB max file content. The filesystem comes pre-populated:

@code{
/
+-- home/
|   +-- readme.txt
|   +-- hello.ltl
|   +-- spiral.txt
+-- etc/
|   +-- hostname    → "lateralus"
|   +-- motd        → "Welcome to LateralusOS v0.1.0"
+-- tmp/
}

Full API: @code{ramfs_create}, @code{ramfs_mkdir}, @code{ramfs_write},
@code{ramfs_read}, @code{ramfs_find}, @code{ramfs_list}, @code{ramfs_remove},
@code{ramfs_resolve_path}.

The VFS is integrated into both the text-mode shell and the GUI terminal.

@subsection{PC Speaker Driver}

PIT Channel 2 tone generation with a non-blocking melody queue (8 notes max).
Programs ports 0x42, 0x43, and 0x61 directly.

Pre-built sound effects:
@list{
  @item{@bold{Boot chime}: C5→E5→G5→C6 ascending arpeggio at startup}
  @item{@bold{Window open}: A5→D6 two-note chime when creating a window}
  @item{@bold{Key click}: 1200 Hz, 3 ms ultra-short feedback}
  @item{@bold{Error beep}: A3 warning tone}
  @item{@bold{Notification}: E6 ding}
}

@subsection{Cooperative Task Scheduler}

A lightweight callback-based scheduler running alongside the main loop.
16 task slots, round-robin execution with configurable intervals.

@code[ltl]{
// Register a periodic task
task_create("cursor_blink", blink_fn, NULL, 500)  // every 500ms

// Register a one-shot delayed task
task_create_oneshot("chime", chime_fn, NULL, 2000, tick)  // after 2s
}

Viewable via the terminal @code{tasks} command.

@subsection{Animated Wallpaper}

The static gradient wallpaper is replaced with a fully animated one:

@list{
  @item{@bold{Color-cycling gradient}: Background colors shift via integer sine/cosine tables (64 entries)}
  @item{@bold{12 twinkling stars}: Pseudo-random positions with brightness that fades in and out}
  @item{@bold{5 Fibonacci spiral rings}: Rotating dots in Catppuccin accent colors (blue, green, yellow, pink, lavender)}
  @item{@bold{Pulsing logo}: "LateralusOS" text with oscillating glow color}
}

All animation uses integer math only (no floating point in freestanding mode).
Phase-based: @code{wallpaper_phase} increments every @code{gui_tick}.

@subsection{Window Animations}

Smooth transitions for window lifecycle events:

@list{
  @item{@bold{Open}: 8-frame scale-from-center animation}
  @item{@bold{Close}: 7-frame shrink-to-center animation}
  @item{@bold{Minimize}: 7-frame slide-to-taskbar animation}
}

New @code{Window} fields: @code{anim_state} (none/opening/closing/minimizing)
and @code{anim_frame} (0-based frame counter).

@subsection{Alt+Tab Window Switcher}

An overlay panel listing all visible windows with a highlighted selection.
@code{Alt+Tab} cycles forward, @code{Shift+Alt+Tab} cycles backward.
Releasing the Alt key focuses the selected window (restores if minimized).

@subsection{Keyboard Enhancements}

@list{
  @item{@bold{Ctrl key tracking}: Scancodes 0x1D/0x9D, generates ASCII control codes}
  @item{@bold{Alt key tracking}: Scancodes 0x38/0xB8, enables Alt+Tab}
  @item{@bold{Ctrl+T}: Open new terminal}
  @item{@bold{Ctrl+A}: Toggle start menu}
  @item{@bold{Ctrl+M}: Open system monitor}
}

@section{Lateralus Companion Files}

Every C module has a corresponding @code{.ltl} implementation:

@list{
  @item{@code{gui/terminal.ltl} — Full terminal emulator in Lateralus}
  @item{@code{gui/wallpaper.ltl} — Animated wallpaper engine with sine tables}
  @item{@code{gui/animation.ltl} — Window animation state machine with easing functions}
  @item{@code{drivers/speaker.ltl} — PIT Channel 2 speaker driver with melody queue}
  @item{@code{fs/vfs.ltl} — Updated with full RAMFS backend (~180 new lines)}
  @item{@code{kernel/scheduler.ltl} — Updated with cooperative task scheduler section}
}

These represent the language-native implementation that will eventually replace
the C stubs once the Lateralus-to-C transpiler can handle all the freestanding
patterns.

@section{Build Metrics}

@table{
  @header{Metric | Value}
  @row{Build steps | 11 (up from 7)}
  @row{Object files | 11 .o files linked}
  @row{Kernel size | 375 KB (up from 136 KB)}
  @row{ISO size | 13 MB}
  @row{Compiler warnings | 0}
  @row{Boot test | PASSED (QEMU serial verified)}
  @row{Language tests | 1,158 passing (zero regressions)}
}

@section{What's Next}

Phase 4 is on the horizon. Candidates include:
@list{
  @item{Persistent storage (ATA/AHCI disk driver)}
  @item{Process isolation and preemptive scheduling}
  @item{Network stack (virtio-net)}
  @item{.ltl script execution from the terminal}
  @item{GUI text editor for .ltl files}
}

@italic{Spiral Out, Keep Going.}

  </script>
